{
  "texts": [
    "It is generally considered that when I 2 < 25%, the heterogeneity between studies is low; when I 2 is between 25 and 50%, heterogeneity is moderate; and when I 2 > 75%, heterogeneity is high (Higgins et al., 2003).",
    "In our current study, as shown in Table 2, the Q-value is 577.66, with a corresponding p-value of 0.00001, which is significantly less than 0.1, indicating substantial heterogeneity among the studies.",
    "Moreover, I 2 = 78%, exceeding 75%, suggesting that the studies have a high level of heterogeneity.",
    "Therefore, to obtain more precise and reliable meta-analysis results, we have decided to use a random-effects model for the meta-analysis.",
    "In this study, we use the Standardized Mean Difference (SMD) as the effect size to assess the impact of project-based learning on students' CT outcomes."
  ]
}